{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617562"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:14:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16475"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16475"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0.03,0.09,0.03,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71203"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9166"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16475"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56677"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"464"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"1394"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4875"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8512"},{"type":"tags","id":"8525"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21770"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71203","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71203"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to her GP with a three-month history of progressive muscle weakness and fatigue. She reports double vision and drooping eyelids that worsen as the day progresses. She has difficulty swallowing and speaking. Her limb weakness worsens after physical activity but improves with rest. She has no pain or sensory changes. Her medical history includes systemic lupus erythematosus and rheumatoid arthritis, for which she takes hydroxychloroquine and methotrexate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she has bilateral ptosis and weakness of extraocular muscles. Limb power is reduced but improves with rest. Deep tendon reflexes and sensation are normal. A computed tomography scan of the chest shows thymic enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the underlying pathophysiology of this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autoantibody-mediated destruction of acetylcholine receptors","Inflammatory demyelination of peripheral nerves","Complement-mediated damage to motor neuron cell bodies","Calcium channel dysfunction at nerve terminals","Impaired acetylcholine synthesis in motor neurons"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of myasthenia gravis, including fatigable weakness particularly affecting ocular, bulbar and limb muscles. The presence of thymic abnormalities and other autoimmune conditions supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoantibody-mediated destruction of acetylcholine receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct pathophysiology. In myasthenia gravis, autoantibodies target and destroy acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction, leading to impaired neuromuscular transmission and fatigable weakness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory demyelination of peripheral nerves\u003C/strong\u003E describes conditions like Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome or chronic inflammatory demyelinating polyneuropathy, which typically present with symmetric weakness and sensory changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplement-mediated damage to motor neuron cell bodies\u003C/strong\u003E is not a recognised mechanism in common neuromuscular disorders.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium channel dysfunction at nerve terminals\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in Lambert-Eaton myasthenic syndrome, which typically presents with proximal muscle weakness that improves with exercise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImpaired acetylcholine synthesis in motor neurons\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary mechanism in myasthenia gravis, which involves receptor destruction rather than neurotransmitter synthesis problems.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Myasthenia gravis is caused by autoantibodies that destroy acetylcholine receptors at the neuromuscular junction.","Fatigable weakness, particularly of ocular and bulbar muscles, is the hallmark of myasthenia gravis.","Thymic abnormalities are present in approximately 75% of myasthenia gravis patients."],"references":["Dresser L, Wlodarski R, Rezania K, Soliven B. Myasthenia Gravis: Epidemiology, Pathophysiology and Clinical Manifestations. J Clin Med. 2021 May 21;10(11):2235. doi: 10.3390/jcm10112235. PMID: 34064035; PMCID: PMC8196750.","Aarli JA, Gilhus NE, Lisak RP, Mantegazza R, Suzuki S. Myasthenia gravis. Autoimmune Dis. 2011;2011:697575. doi: 10.4061/2011/697575. Epub 2012 Jan 24. PMID: 22312479; PMCID: PMC3270513.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Mishra AK, Varma A. Myasthenia Gravis: A Systematic Review. Cureus. 2023 Dec 6;15(12):e50017. doi: 10.7759/cureus.50017. PMID: 38186498; PMCID: PMC10767470."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56677"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questi